INSERT INTO `paper` VALUES ('A branching process approximation to cascading load-dependent system failure','IEEE','not-in-selection',2004,'','','proceedings'),('A complex network based model for detecting isolated communities in water distribution networks','AIP','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('A framework of enroute air traffic conflict detection and resolution through complex network analysis','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('A geometric approach to robustness in complex networks','IEEE','not-in-selection',2011,'','','proceedings'),('A graph-theoretic perspective on centrality','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2006,'','','journal'),('A greedy heuristic for the set-covering problem','INFORMS','not-in-selection',1979,'','','journal'),('A high-robustness and low-cost model for cascading failures','IOP','not-in-selection',2007,'','','joural'),('A knowledge generation model via the hypernetwork','PLS','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('A measure of individual role in collective dynamics','arXiv','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),('A model for cascading failures in scale-free networks with a breakdown probability','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('A model of Internet topology using k-shell decomposition','NAS','not-in-selection',2007,'','','journal'),('A multilayer-routing-strategy with dynamic link resource adaptation','Springer','not-in-selection',2005,'','','collection'),('A new nonlocal traffic flow model with anticipation-dependent relaxation time, equilibrium velocity and variance','IOP','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),('A probabilistic loading-dependent model of cascading failure and possible implications for blackouts','IEEE','not-in-selection',2003,'','','proceedings'),('A property of eigenvectors of nonnegative symmetric matrices and its application to graph theory','ASCzechR','not-in-selection',1975,'','','journal'),('A set of measures of centrality based on betweenness','JSTOR','not-in-selection',1977,'','','journal'),('A simple model of global cascades on random networks','NAS','not-in-selection',2002,'','','journal'),('A Study of the Effect of Basic Network Characteristics on System-of-System Failure Propagation','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('A survey of network virtualization','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),('ABNO: A feasible SDN approach for multivendor IP and optical networks [invited]','OSA','not-in-selection',2015,'','','journal'),('Abnormal cascading on complex networks','APS','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Abrupt transition in the structural formation of interconnected networks','nature','nphys2761',2013,'Our world is linked by a complex mesh of networks through which information, people and goods flow. These networks are interdependent on each other, and present structural and dynamical features1–6 different from those observed in isolated networks7–9. Although examples of such dissimilar properties are becoming more abundant—such as in diffusion, robustness and competition—it is not yet clear where these differences are rooted. Here we show that the process of building independent networks into an interconnected network of networks under- goes a structurally sharp transition as the interconnections are formed. Depending on the relative importance of inter- and intra- layer connections, we find that the entire interdependent system can be tuned between two regimes: in one regime, the various layers are structurally decoupled and they act as independent entities; in the other regime, network layers are indistinguishable and the whole system behaves as a single- level network.  We analytically show that the transition between the two regimes is discontinuous even for finite-size networks. Thus, any real-world interconnected system is potentially at risk of abrupt changes in its structure, which may manifest new dynamical properties.','This paper presents a way to study the structure of a interdependent network through an augmented matrix and it\'s \'supra-laplacian\' it\'s shown. To do so the Fiedler vector of the graph is used to analyze the structure of it, this vector is studied as a function of p, the weight factor for the interdependent nodes. A detailed analysis of the Fiedler vector is presented and it\'s shown a connection between the percolation treshold of an interdependent network and the \'p\' that points the discontinuity of the vector on function of p. It\'s concluded that this kind of study is a practical way to study the resilience of a network of any size.','journal'),('Abruptness of cascade failures in power grids','nature','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('Accuracy of mean-field theory for dynamics on real-world networks','APS','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),('Advances in neural information processing systems','MITPress','not-in-selection',2006,'','','book'),('Algebraic connectivity of graphs','ASCzechR','not-in-selection',1973,'','','journal'),('Algebraic connectivity of interdependent networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('Algebraic connectivity optimization via link addition','ICST','not-in-selection',2008,'','','proceedings'),('Algorithm 447: efficient algorithms for graph manipulation','ACM','not-in-selection',1973,'','','journal'),('Algorithm to determine the percolation largest component in interconnected networks','APS','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('An electrical betweenness approach for vulnerability assessment of power grids considering the capacity of generators and load','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('An exploratory analysis on the evolution of the US airport network','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('An imperfect competition on scale-free networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('An improved framework for power grid vulnerability analysis considering critical system features','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('An improved model for structural vulnerability analysis of power networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('An initial model for complex dynamics in electric power system blackouts','Citeseer','not-in-selection',2001,'','','proceedings'),('An Overlay Mapping Model for Achieving Enhanced QoS and Resilience Performance','IEEE','6078855',2011,'In this paper, we investigate the issue of how to map an application request upon a substrate network in such a way that the selected hosting node and link sets can provide not only enhanced Quality-of-Service (QoS) but also resilience against potential substrate link failure(s). Different from previous works which only strive to solve this problem heuristically, this paper formulates it as an Integer Linear Program (ILP). In multi-layer networks, diversity of the working and backup paths is important because a single link failure in the lower layer can result in failures of all the upper-layer links that go through it. Thus, we further strengthen the proposed ILP model by incorporating the objective of finding effective backup paths during the application request mapping process. This is achieved by exploiting the substrate topology information.  The effectiveness of the proposed ILP model is verified through extensive simulations. This novel ILP model is proved to perform significantly better in terms of QoS performance as compared to the heuristic solutions. Moreover, the proposed ILP model can provide diversified working and backup paths using few additional substrate nodes.','In this paper they talk about a substrate network (physical network) and overlay network (computer network that is built on top of another network. Nodes in the overlay network can be thought of as being connected by virtual or logical links, each of which corresponds to a path, perhaps through many physical links, in the underlying network). To tackle the problem \"given a substrate network with QoS and candidate information, how should one place an overlay request with QoS constraints so as to maximize the performance of the mapped overlay whilst increasing its resilience with the least substrate resources possible\" is developed in the paper an Integer Lineal Program model that can solve the overlay mapping of nodes and edges while achieving enhanced QoS and resilience performance. The ILP model is also improved to secure diversified working and backup paths allocation. Finally through extensive simulations, the proposed overlay mapping model is proved to perform better than QoSmap (the latest one at that moment).','proceedings'),('Analysis of communication network performance from a complex network perspective','IEEE','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Analysis of fracture network connectivity using percolation theory','Springer','not-in-selection',1995,'','','journal'),('Analysis of percolation behaviors of clustered networks with partial support--dependence relations','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('Analysis of percolation behaviors of clustered networks with partial support–dependence relations','ScienceDirect','Analysis-of-percolation',2014,'We carry out a study of percolation behaviors of clustered networks with partial support–dependence relations by adopting two different attacking strategies, attacking only one network and both networks, which help to further understand real coupled networks. For two different attacking strategies we find that the system changes from a second-order phase transition to a first-order phase transition as coupling strength q increases. We also notice that the first-order region becomes smaller and the second-order region becomes larger as average degree or clustering coefficient increases. And, as the average supported degree approaches infinity, coupled clustered networks become independent and only the second-order transition is observed, which is similar to q = 0. Furthermore, we find that clustering coefficient has a significant impact on robustness of the system for strong coupling strength, but for weak coupling strength it has little influence, especially for attacking both networks. The study implies that we can obtain a more robust network by reducing clustering coefficient and increasing average degree for strong coupling strength. However, for weak coupling strength, a more robust network is obtained only by increasing average degree for the same support average degree. Additionally, we find that for attacking both networks the system becomes more vulnerable and difficult to defend compared to attacking only one network.','A percolation threshold study is performed for networks with different characteristics. They vary the coupling coefficient q , the clustering coefficient c, and the place in the network where the attacks are performed (network A, B or both). They consider: 1.- a functional node must have at least one functional support node in other networks 2.- a functional node must belong to the giant component of functional nodes in the network it belongs to. They find that depending on the attack strategy the system shows behaviors of first order and second order phase transition, they observe that the region of first order phase transition becomes smaller, while the region of second order phase transition becomes larger as ⟨k⟩ (average node degree) or c increases. As average supported degree k ̃ → ∞ (this degree is the amount of nodes that support others), coupled clustered networks become independent and behave similarly to a single clustered network. And the system becomes robust as ⟨k⟩ increases for the different clustered coefficients. For strong coupling strength, pAc (critical threshold of net A) or pc (critical/percolation threshold) increases and the system becomes vulnerable as c increases. However, as c changes, pAc or pc don\'t change significantly for weak coupling strength. Finally they find that the networks are more vulnerable when both parts are attacked at the same time.','journal'),('Analyzing cascading failures in smart grids under random and targeted attacks','IEEE','not-in-selection',2014,'','','proceedings'),('Analyzing cross-sector interdependencies','IEEE','not-in-selection',2007,'','','proceedings'),('Application of predictive control strategies to the management of complex networks in the urban water cycle [applications of control]','IEEE','not-in-selection',2013,'','','proceedings'),('Approximate model of European interconnected system as a benchmark system to study effects of cross-border trades','IEEE','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),('Architecture for the Automatically Switched Optical Network (ASON)','G','not-in-selection',2001,'','','-'),('Are randomly grown graphs really random?','APS','not-in-selection',2001,'','','journal'),('Assessing the impact of geographically correlated network failures','IEEE','not-in-selection',2008,'','','proceedings'),('Assessing the vulnerability of the fiber infrastructure to disasters','IEEE','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Assortativity decreases the robustness of interdependent networks','APS','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),('Attack and error tolerance of complex networks','nature','not-in-selection',2000,'','','journal'),('Attack structural vulnerability of power grids: A hybrid approach based on complex networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),('Attack vulnerability of complex communication networks','IEEE','not-in-selection',2008,'','','journal'),('Attack vulnerability of complex networks','APS','not-in-selection',2002,'','','journal'),('Attack vulnerability of scale-free networks due to cascading breakdown','APS','not-in-selection',2004,'','','journal'),('Attack vulnerability of scale-free networks due to cascading failures','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2008,'','','journal'),('Automorphic forms and geometry of arithmetic varieties','Academic Press','not-in-selection',2014,'','','book'),('Avalanche collapse of interdependent networks','APS','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),('Avoiding catastrophic failure in correlated networks of networks','nature','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('Balancing system survivability and cost of smart grid via modeling cascading failures','IEEE','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Betweenness centrality in a weighted network','APS','not-in-selection',2008,'','','journal'),('BioGRID: a general repository for interaction datasets','Oxford Un.','not-in-selection',2006,'','','journal'),('Biological networks: the tinkerer as an engineer','AAAS','not-in-selection',2003,'','','journal'),('Breakdown of the Internet under intentional attack','APS','not-in-selection',2001,'','','journal'),('Bridging centrality: identifying bridging nodes in scale-free networks','','not-in-selection',2006,'','','proceedings'),('Capacity efficiency and restorability of path protection and rerouting in WDM networks subject to dual failures','Springer','not-in-selection',2004,'','','journal'),('CAPEX savings by a scalable IP offloading approach','OSA','not-in-selection',2011,'','','proceedings'),('Cascade control and defense in complex networks','APS','not-in-selection',2004,'','','journal'),('Cascade of failures in coupled network systems with multiple support-dependence relations','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Cascade of failures in interdependent networks coupled by different type networks','ScienceDirect','Cascade-of-failures-in-interd',2015,'Modern systems are mostly coupled together. Therefore, they should be modeled as interdependent networks. In this paper, the robustness of interdependent networks coupled with different type networks is studied in detail under both targeted and random attack. The critical fraction of nodes leading to a complete fragmentation of two interdependent networks is analyzed. Some findings are summarized as: (i) For random attack problem, the existence criteria for the giant component in interdependent networks coupled by two dif- ferent type networks are quite different from those coupled by the same type networks. Different type coupled networks are more vulnerable than the same type coupled-networks. (ii) For targeted attack problem, if the highly connected nodes are protected and only the lowly connected nodes failed, the system leads to a first order percolation phase transition for different type coupled-networks, and a second transition for same type coupled-networks as well. The available result implies that different type coupled-networks are difficult to defend by strategies such as protecting the high degree nodes that can be useful to significantly improve robustness of the same type coupled-networks. (iii) For targeted attack problem, when the lowly connected nodes are protected and only the highly connected nodes failed, coupled scale free networks become more vulnerable than the others.','This paper confronts the problem of the homogeneity in the networks that are coupled in many studies. Most of the papers assume that the networks coupled are, structuraly speaking, the same. For example it\'s really common to see 2 scale-free networks coupled together or 2 erdos-renyi. However, the authors argue, that this is not the case in real life. So this paper compares the behavior of same type networks coupled vs different type. They also test its behaviour by protecting high or low degree nodes. They use one to one coupling and test percolation thresholds to look up the resilience of the networks under attack. It is found that: Different type coupled-networks are more vulnerable than the same type coupled-networks. Different type coupled-networks are difficult to defend by strategies such as protecting the high degree nodes. If only lowly connected nodes were attacked, the system can still lead to a first order percolation phase transition. If only the highly connected nodes were attacked, coupled scale free networks become more vulnerable than the others.','journal'),('Cascade-based attack vulnerability on the US power grid','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Cascade-based attacks on complex networks','APS','not-in-selection',2002,'','','journal'),('Cascaded failures in weighted networks','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Cascades on a class of clustered random networks','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Cascades on correlated and modular random networks','APS','not-in-selection',2008,'','','journal'),('Cascading dynamics in congested complex networks','Springer','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Cascading dynamics on random networks: Crossover in phase transition','APS','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),('Cascading dynamics with local weighted flow redistribution in interdependent networks','Springer','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Cascading failure in Watts--Strogatz small-world networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),('Cascading failure spreading on weighted heterogeneous networks','IOP','not-in-selection',2008,'','','journal'),('Cascading failure tolerance of modular small-world networks','IEEE','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Cascading failures and the emergence of cooperation in evolutionary-game based models of social and economical networks','AIP','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Cascading failures in bi-partite graphs: model for systemic risk propagation','nature','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Cascading failures in complex infrastructure systems','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Cascading failures in coupled map lattices','APS','not-in-selection',2004,'','','journal'),('Cascading failures in interconnected networks with dynamical redistribution of loads','ScienceDirect','Cascade-of-failures-in-interc',2015,'Cascading failures of loads in isolated networks and coupled networks have been studied in the past few years. In most of the corresponding results, the topologies of the networks are destroyed. Here, we present an interconnected network model considering cascading failures based on the dynamic redistribution of flow in the networks. Compared with the results of single scale-free networks, we find that interconnected scale-free networks have higher vulnerability. Additionally, the network heterogeneity plays an important role in the robustness of interconnected networks under intentional attacks. Considering the effects of various coupling preferences, the results show that there are almost no differences. Finally, the application of our model to the Beijing interconnected traffic network, which consists of a subway network and a bus network, shows that the subway network suffers more damage under the attack. Moreover, the interconnected traffic network may be more exposed to damage after initial attacks on the bus network. These discussions are important for the design and optimization of interconnected networks.','This paper studies flow dinamics on interconnected networks. They assume that each node in a network can manage a given amount of load and have an \"alpha\": tolerance parameter that helps to determine the load capacity. They test 3 types of coupling Random Coupling, Asortative Coupling, Dissasortative Coupling. Whenever a node is removed the load is redistributed, this may cause that some nodes become congested. When a node gets congested their counterparts in the other networks receive the overflow. This whole approach have a transpotation focus (bus - subway networks) which explains the model. In this paper 2 types of attack are tested: random and targeted to the node with the highest load. On each test it is considered that only 1 node is removed due to the attack and then the consecuent cascading failures end the attack. To measure robustness \"global efficiency is used\". The coupling kind assumed is one to one and the simulated data of networks come from ER-ER and SF-SF networks with the same amount of nodes. The real \"Traffic networks of beijing city\" are used to test the attacks too, in this case the bus and metro network are used but they don\'t have the same amount of nodes so each node of the subway network is conected to the \"corresponding\" bus station but not every bus station is connected to a subway station. Findings: Enhancing the heterogeneity between nodes will make networks more susceptible.The coupling preference makes almost no differences to the resilience. ','journal'),('Cascading failures in interdependent lattice networks: The critical role of the length of dependency links','APS','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),('Cascading failures in multiple infrastructures: From transportation to communication network','IEEE','not-in-selection',2010,'','','proceedings'),('Cascading failures in power grids','IEEE','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Cascading Failures in Smart Grid: Joint Effect of Load Propagation and Interdependence','IEEE','7348643',2015,'The smart grid mainly suffers from two types of cascading failures: 1) interdependence cascading failure and 2) load propagation cascading failure. The former one happens due to the interdependence between power grid and communication networks. The latter one is caused by the load propagation in the single power grid. A tiny failure leads to the simultaneous occurrence of these two cascading failures. In this paper, we study the system robustness by considering the interdependence and load propagation. First, we develop a mathematical tool to analyze the load propagation in single network. Then, a percolation- based method is proposed to calculate the remaining fractions of survivals after the cascading failures stop. We estimate the node tolerance parameter T (the ratio of capacity to initial workload) threshold Tc′, below which the entire system may suffer from the cascading failure.The effect of interdependence on Tc′ is also studied, where lower Tc′ is required for the less compact interdependence. We prove that the system performance approaches to the upper bound once the tolerance parameter T → ∞. Our analysis indicates that the fraction of survivals in the power grid is always greater than that in communication network, although the initial failure occurs in the power grid. The extensive simulations validate our mathematical analysis, and demonstrate that the relation between the number of initial failures and tolerance parameter threshold is super-linear.','A novel framework is proposed where the model of the interdependent networks are not only subjected to the cascading failures due to the interconected nature of the network but also due to load failures (takes into account flow stuff). This work consider power and communication networks coupled together by the \"k-n\" model. Nodes in the power network have a tolerance parameter which helps determine how much load they can take. Using techniques similar to percolation threshold, they estimate the final size of the largest connected component after cascading failures. They look at the effect of both types of cascading failures (interconection and load+inteconection) on the network giving a more realistic view of the communication-power coupling.','journal'),('Cascading failures of loads in interconnected networks under intentional attack','IOP','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Cascading link failure in the power grid: A percolation-based analysis','IEEE','not-in-selection',2011,'','','proceedings'),('Cascading load model in interdependent networks with coupled strength','ScienceDirect','Cascading-load',2015,'Considering the coupled strength between interdependent networks, we introduce a new method to define the initial load on an edge and propose a cascading load model in interdependent networks. We explore the robustness of the interdependent networks against cascading failures by two measures, i.e., the critical threshold βc quantifying the whole robustness of the interdependent networks to avoid the emergence of cascading failure, and the new proposed smallest capacity threshold βc,s quantifying the degree of the worst damage of the interdependent networks. We numerically find that the AL (high-degree nodes in network A connect high-degree ones in network B) link between two networks can greatly enhance the robust level of the interdependent networks against cascading failures. Especially we observe that the values of βc in the interdependent networks with both the DL (high-degree nodes in network A connect low-degree ones in network B) link and the RL (nodes in network A randomly connect ones in network B) link increase monotonically with the coupled strength, while the values of βc,s in the interdependent networks with three types of link patterns almost monotonically decreases with the coupled strength. In the interdependent networks with the AL,the value of βc first decreases and then increases with the coupled strength. We further explain this interesting phenomenon by a simple graph. In addition, we study the influence of the coupled strength on the efficiency of two attacks to destroy the interdependent networks. We find that, when the coupled strength between two networks is weaker, attacking the edges with the lower load is more easier to trigger the cascading propagation than attacking the nodes with the higher load, however, when the coupled strength in two networks is stronger, the case is on the contrary. Finally, we give reasonable explanations from the local perspective of the total capacity of all neighboring edges of a failed edge.','In this paper networks are considered to have load capacities, coupling strength and cascading failures due to overload. This paper focuses on attacks towards edges and the subsequent effect of this on the load of the networks. In this case if a node becomes overloaded it fails and therefore their coupled counterpart fails too, spreading the problem. If an edge fails the overload is redistributed on the same network. The aproach is a one-to-one bidirectional coupling and the nodes are coupled: High-high degrees (AL), high-low degreed (DL), random (RL). The robustness is measured in three ways: The average amount of edges lost after a cascading failure (avalanche), the beta at which the graph presents a phase transition, and the smallest capacity threshold. (beta is the coefficient that determines the capacity). They also define the coupled strength wij between interconnected nodes in different networks  w_{im}=(k_{i}k_{m})^α. WWith the coupling strength the initial load is calculated (with this + beta we get the capacity). The attacks strategies used: attacking the edges with the higher load (HL),  attacking the edges with the lower load (LL). \"We find that the robustness of the interdependent networks with the assortative link pattern is greatly improved than the other two link patterns. The interesting result is that the coupled strength plays the different roles in three types of link patterns. When the coupled strength is weaker, the edges with the lower load play an important role in the cascading propagation, which gives us an implication that protecting these intuitive unimportant edges may dramatically enhance the robustness of the interdependent networks.\"','journal'),('Catastrophic cascade of failures in interdependent networks','nature','nature08932',2010,'Complex networks have been studied intensively for a decade, but research still focuses on the limited case of a single, non-interacting network1–14. Modern systems are coupled together15–19 and there- fore should be modelled as interdependent networks. A fun- damental property of interdependent networks is that failure of nodes in one network may lead to failure of dependent nodes in other networks. This may happen recursively and can lead to a cascade of failures. In fact, a failure of a very small fraction of nodes in one network may lead to the complete fragmentation of a system of several interdependent networks. A dramatic real-world example of a cascade of failures (‘concurrent malfunction’) is the electrical blackout that affected much of Italy on 28 September 2003: the shutdown of power stations directly led to the failure of nodes in the Internet communication network, which in turn caused further breakdown of power stations20. Here we develop a framework for understanding the robustness of interacting networks subject to such cascading failures. We present exact ana- lytical solutions for the critical fraction of nodes that, on removal, will lead to a failure cascade and to a complete fragmentation of two interdependent networks. Surprisingly, a broader degree distri- bution increases the vulnerability of interdependent networks to random failure, which is opposite to how a single network behaves. Our findings highlight the need to consider interdependent network properties in designing robust networks.','The paper presents the situation of the 2003 blackout on Italy as a start point to develop a framework that allows the study of interdependent networks with cascading failures. First the paper explains how does their model of interdependent networks works in detail, taking into acount the steps that the interdependent network faces on a cascading failure. Then the theory of the model is explained as well as its behaviour in terms of percolation. The model is solved for some network distributions by using the generating function approach. The framework is also tested using simulations for some interconected networks where the distribution and quiantity of nodes vary.','journal'),('Centrality in social networks conceptual clarification','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',1978,'','','journal'),('Characterization and modeling of weighted networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),('Characterization of complex networks: A survey of measurements','Taylor \\& Francis','not-in-selection',2007,'','','journal'),('Classes of small-world networks','NAS','not-in-selection',2000,'','','journal'),('Cluster structure near the percolation threshold','IOP','not-in-selection',1982,'','','journal'),('Collective dynamics of ‘small-world’ networks','nature','not-in-selection',1998,'','','journal'),('Combinatorial landscapes','SIAM','not-in-selection',2002,'','','journal'),('Communication and correlation among communities','APS','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Community structure and ethnic preferences in school friendship networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2007,'','','journal'),('Complex network clustering by multiobjective discrete particle swarm optimization based on decomposition','IEEE','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('Complex networks, vol. 650','Springer','not-in-selection',2004,'','','misc'),('Complex networks: A winning strategy','nature','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Complex networks: structure and dynamics','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2006,'','','journal'),('Complex networks: structure, robustness and function','CUP','not-in-selection',2010,'','','book'),('Complex networks: The fragility of interdependency','NPG','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),('Complex systems analysis of series of blackouts: Cascading failure, critical points, and self-organization','AIP','not-in-selection',2007,'','','journal'),('Complexity of coupled human and natural systems','AAAS','not-in-selection',2007,'','','journal'),('Component criticality in failure cascade processes of network systems','WOL','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Computers and intractability','WHFreemanNY','not-in-selection',2002,'','','book'),('Computing global structural balance in large-scale signed social networks','NAS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Concepts in thermal physics','OUP Oxford','not-in-selection',2009,'','','book'),('Conditions for viral influence spreading through multiplex correlated social networks','APS','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('Conficker C analysis','SRIInt','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Contact-based social contagion in multiplex networks','APS','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Controllability of complex networks','nature','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Coordinated scheduling of electricity and natural gas infrastructures with a transient model for natural gas flow','AIP','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Correlated couplings and robustness of coupled networks','arXiv','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),('Coupled behavior analysis with applications','IEEE','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),('Critical Cascading Failures in Interdependent Networks: Non Mean-Field Behavior','arXiv','not-in-selection',2012,'','','preprint'),('Critical effect of dependency groups on the function of networks','NAS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Critical load and congestion instabilities in scale-free networks','IOP','not-in-selection',2003,'','','journal'),('Critical phenomena in complex networks','APS','not-in-selection',2008,'','','journal'),('Cross-layer survivability in WDM-based networks','IEEE','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Data mining with big data','IEEE','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('Decreasing the spectral radius of a graph by link removals','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Design and evolution of modular neural network architectures','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',1994,'','','journal'),('Design of Robust Dependent Networks against Flow-based Cascading Failures','IEEE','7014931',2014,'In this paper we propose strategies to increase the robustness of a communication network which depends on the proper functioning of an electricity network. The strategies involve selecting nodes of the communication network and removing their dependency on the electricity network. Compared to existing literature on this topic, such as Schneider et al. [1], we use a more realistic model of the electricity network by taking the essential characteristics of the power flow into account, instead of considering purely the topological structure. The effect of the flow-based cascading failures originating from the electrical grid, on the communication network is studied, where the coupling between those networks plays an important role. We have computed the performanceof our proposed selection strategies by averaging over many configurations of communication networks, which are modelled both as scale-free networks and as Erdos-Renyi random graphs, applied to an electricity network formed by the IEEE 118  bus test system. We show that a hybrid strategy, based on the degree of the communication nodes and the failure probabilities of the electricity nodes, give a significant improvement over a random selection strategy, as well as over other strategies we proposed. Our method is also tested on a real-world interdependent network: the high voltage electricity grid in Italy coupled with a communication network, inspired by the Italy blackout in 2003.','This paper treat the topic of communication-power grid networks taking into account flow dynamics on the electric network and a one directional coupling model. Here is stated that the power grid does not depend on the standar communication network but rather on its own SCADA network and that communication network does depend on the electricity network. In order to design a more robust network, since is too expensive to redesign a network they propose to have some communication nodes decoupled by making them self suficient. They too say that this can be done just for some nodes due to the costs involved. On this model they use equations to simulate the flow of energy through the electricity network, whenever a node exceeds or lower its flow enough it becomes non-functional. In this paper several \'robusting\' strategies are proved (1.-The reference scenario, where no nodes are autonomous.2.-Nodes from the communication network or electricity network are chosen uniformly random.3.-Nodes with the highest degree in the electricity network are chosen.5.-Nodes with the lowest degree in the electricity network are chosen.6.-Nodes with the highest probability to fail in the electricity network are chosen.7.-Linear hybrid of strategy 3 and 6.7.-Non-linear hybrid of strategy 3 and 6), being the hybrid strategies (degree + probability of collapse) the most effective at improving the robustness of the coupled system against random attacks.','proceedings'),('Designing and embedding reliable virtual infrastructures','ACM','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Designing resilient networks using a hybrid genetic algorithm approach','ACM','not-in-selection',2005,'','','proceedings'),('Designing survivable resilient networks: a stochastic hybrid genetic algorithm approach','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2007,'','','journal'),('Detecting Critical Nodes in Interdependent Power Networks for Vulnerability Assessment','IEEE','6407159',2013,'Power networks and information systems become more and more interdependent to ensure better supports for the functionality as well as improve the economy. However, power networks also tend to be more vulnerable due to the cascading failures from their interdependent information systems, i.e., the failures in the information systems can cause the failures of the coupled portion in power networks. Therefore, the accurate vulnerability assessment of interdependent power networks is of great importance in the presence of unexpected disruptive events or adversarial attacks targeting on critical network nodes. In this paper, we study the Interdependent Power Network Disruptor (IPND) optimization problem to identify critical nodes in an in- terdependent power network whose removals maximally destroy its functions due to both malfunction of these nodes and the cascading failures of its interdependent communication network. First, we show the IPND problem is NP-hard to be approximated within the factor of ￼ (2 - epsilon). Despite its intractability, we propose a greedy framework with novel centrality functions based on the networks’ interdependencies, to efficiently solve this problem in a timely manner. An extensive experiment not only illustrates the effectiveness of our approach on networks with different topolo- gies and interdependencies, but also highlights some important observations which help to sharpen the robustness of interdependent networks in the future.','It begins by explaining the cascading failure and interdependent networks model. Then it shows that the IPND (Interdependent Power Network Disruptor:  identify critical nodes in an interdependent power network whose removals maximally destroy its functions due to both malfunction of these nodes and the cascading failures of its interdependent communication network) problem is NP-hard and cannot be approximated, so they proceed to propose a greedy framework and centrality measues extended to fit the interconected nature of the networks. For these they perform experimental tests and find many improvements on the proposed versus what there was before.The problem here consist on \"Given an integer ￼k and an interdependent system, the IPND problem asks for a set ￼ of size at most ￼k such that minimazes the size of the largest component\" The greedy strategies proposed consist on removing each time the most critical node. Tree strategies are used to choose the most critical node: node that maximizes the number of failed nodes after the cascading failure,node that decreases the structural strength of the system as much as possible, node that not only increases the number of failed nodes but decreases the structural strength as well. At the end of the work several ways of coupling the networks were tested.','journal'),('Detecting critical nodes in sparse graphs','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Deterministic scale-free networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2001,'','','journal'),('Deterministic scale-free small-world networks of arbitrary order','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Diffusion dynamics on multiplex networks','APS','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Dimension of spatially embedded networks','nature','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Discrete-time Markov chain approach to contact-based disease spreading in complex networks','IOP','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),('Distributed recovery from network partitioning in movable sensor/actor networks via controlled mobility','IEEE','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),('Do topological models provide good information about electricity infrastructure vulnerability?','AIP','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),('Do topological models provide good information about vulnerability in electric power networks?','arXiv','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),('Driving interconnected networks to supercriticality','APS','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('Dual Failure Protection in Multilayer Networks based on Overlay or Augmented Model','IEEE','1563863',2005,'In this paper we present and compare different multilayer networks based on overlay or augmented model, the client is not aware of the routing information of the server layer. Therefore, some resilience mechanisms need new functions that have to be provided by the User Network Interface (UNI). Based on generic building blocks for surviving dual failures we propose four multilayer protection models. We extend our existing simulation software for analyzing resilience options and evaluate the selected operation scenarios.','This paper is mainly focused on client-server layers on computer networks. Basic \"building blocks\" to resist dual failures are presented to increase the robustness of the client-server multilayer network. Using these building blocks 5 multilayer protection models. The models were tested on the pan-european network using 4 cases. There they examine the costs of each model. ','proceedings'),('Dynamic multilayer routing schemes in GMPLS-based IP+ optical networks','IEEE','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),('Dynamical and correlation properties of the Internet','APS','not-in-selection',2001,'','','journal'),('Dynamical interplay between awareness and epidemic spreading in multiplex networks','APS','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Dynamical Processes on Complex Networks','CUP','not-in-selection',2008,'','','journal'),('Economic analysis for transport network evolution','CTTE','not-in-selection',2009,'','','proceedings'),('Economic networks: The new challenges','AAAS','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Edge-based-attack induced cascading failures on scale-free networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Effect of network size on robustness of interconnected networks under targeted attack','ScienceDirect','Effect-of-network',2015,'Cascading failures in coupled networks have been intensively studied recently. The underlying assumption is that all networks share the same size. However, this setting cannot capture real-world coupled networks very well. Hence, in this paper, we explore how different network sizes affect cascades from the perspective of the whole interconnected networks. We find that when two networks with similar sizes are coupled, the interconnected networks are the most fragile for sparse coupling while they are the most robust for dense coupling. Moreover, we also study the effect of network size on the robustness of individual network. We find that when two networks with different sizes are coupled, the larger one is more robust for sparse coupling, while more fragile for dense coupling.','Here a framework that considers flows and capacities on its model is presented. Unlike other similar models this consider that the 2 networks paticipating can have different sizes (although they have the same average degree). Characteristics of the model presented in this framework are: there can be a transference of traffic between networks through the interlinks, the coupling is assortative by load order or random depending on the case tested. In this framework the load that each node can take is given by their inicial betweennes centrality pondered by a factor of (1+alfa). The relative size of the largest component after failure G, the relative size of the largest component of one network after failure compared to the total giant component at the moment f(A) and alfa_0,5, the alfa where g=0,5 is used to study the resilience of the network. The size of the original giant component is the sum of the sizes of the two original networks. Once the interconnected system has been attacked and the cascading failure is over, a node must belong to the giant connected component to be functional. Tests were performed for varying amount of interlinks (L), N_b (size of net B), and kind of coupling. For each test 30 to 40 cases were used. They found that interconnected systems with sparse coupling behave almost in an opposite way from the systems with strong coupling. (the attacks choose the nodes with highest load.... with some probability?)','journal'),('Effect of the degree correlation in public goods game on scale-free networks','IOP','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Effect of the interconnected network structure on the epidemic threshold','APS','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Effective usage of shortest paths promotes transportation efficiency on scale-free networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Efficient algorithm to compute mutually connected components in interdependent networks','APS','not-in-selection',2015,'','','journal'),('Efficient and dependable overlay networks','IEEE','not-in-selection',2008,'','','proceedings'),('Efficient behavior of small-world networks','APS','not-in-selection',2001,'','','journal'),('Efficient immunization strategies for computer networks and populations','APS','not-in-selection',2003,'','','journal'),('Efficient recovery of dynamic behavior in coupled oscillator networks','APS','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Efficient response to cascading disaster spreading','APS','not-in-selection',2007,'','','journal'),('Emergence of scaling in random networks','science','not-in-selection',1999,'','','journal'),('Empirical findings on critical infrastructure dependencies in Europe','Springer','not-in-selection',2008,'','','proceedings'),('Enhancing community integrity of networks against multilevel targeted attacks','APS','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Enhancing network performance by edge addition','World Scien.','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Enhancing robustness of coupled networks under targeted recoveries','nature','srep08439',2015,'Coupled networks are extremely fragile because a node failure of a network would trigger a cascade of failures on the entire system. Existing studies mainly focused on the cascading failures and the robustness of coupled networks when the networks suffer from attacks. In reality, it is necessary to recover the damaged networks, and there are cascading failures in recovery processes. In this study, firstly, we analyze the cascading failures of coupled networks during recoveries. Then, a recovery robustness index is presented for evaluating the resilience of coupled networks to cascading failures in the recovery processes.Finally, we propose a technique aiming at protecting several influential nodes for enhancing robustness of coupled networks under the recoveries, and adopt six strategies based on the potential knowledge of network centrality to find the influential nodes. Experiments on three coupling networks demonstrate that with a small number of influential nodes protected, the robustness of coupled networks under the recoveries can be greatly enhanced.','Unlike other works on cascading failures on multilayered networks, here the paper focuses on cascading failures during recoveries. In order to analize this scenareo ithey suggest that there are 4 main point to address: 1.- It is unknown for the model of recovery processes. 2.-There is no mathematical model that can express the cascading failures between coupled networks during recovery.  3.- It is not known how to evaluate recovery robustness of coupled networks. 4.- How to enhance the recovery robustness of coupled networks. The paper proposes a damaged coupled network and analyses its cascading failures during the recovery process. Then proposes an R_rc(robustness recovery) index to evaluate the robustness of coupled networks under recoveries.Finally presents a technique based on the protection of several influential nodes to enhance the robustness of coupled networks under recoveries, here several strategies are tested. To test the performance of the enhancing method ER-ER, ER-SF and Power-SF coupled systems are tested. It is found that the networks that aren\'t coupled with ER\'s networks are the most fragile and the ones that obtain the most benefit from the node protection. It is also found that global strategy protection works best for the non ER-ER coupled networks rather than the local strategies.Lambda is the mixing parameter. The actual info is on \'methods\'.','journal'),('Entangled networks, synchronization, and optimal network topology','APS','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),('Entropy optimization of scale-free networks’ robustness to random failures','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2006,'','','journal'),('Epidemic dynamics and endemic states in complex networks','APS','not-in-selection',2001,'','','journal'),('Epidemic incidence in correlated complex networks','APS','not-in-selection',2003,'','','journal'),('Epidemic spreading in scale-free networks','APS','not-in-selection',2001,'','','journal'),('Epidemic spreading on interconnected networks','APS','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),('Epidemics on interconnected networks','APS','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),('Error and attack tolerance of complex networks','nature','not-in-selection',2000,'','','journal'),('Evolution and Structure of the Internet: A Statistical Physics Approach','APS','not-in-selection',2005,'','','proceedings'),('Evolution of cooperation in multiplex networks','nature','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),('Evolution of cooperation on scale-free networks subject to error and attack','IOP','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Evolution of Networks: From Biological Nets to the Internet and WWW','OUP Oxford','not-in-selection',2013,'','','book'),('Exact controllability of complex networks','nature','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Exact coupling threshold for structural transition reveals diversified behaviors in interconnected networks','APS','not-in-selection',2015,'','','journal'),('Exploring complex networks','nature','not-in-selection',2001,'','','journal'),('Failures propagation in critical interdependent infrastructures','Inderscience','not-in-selection',2008,'','','journal'),('Feedback arc set in bipartite tournaments is NP-complete','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2007,'','','journal'),('FINAL REPORT of the Investigation Committee on the 28 September 2003 Blackout in Italy','UCTE','not-in-selection',2004,'','','misc'),('Fluctuation-driven dynamics of the Internet topology','APS','not-in-selection',2002,'','','journal'),('Forecast and Methodology, 2010--2015, June 1, 2011','CVN Index','not-in-selection',2011,'','','whitepape'),('Fractal boundaries of complex networks','IOP','not-in-selection',2008,'','','journal'),('Fractals and disordered systems','Springer','not-in-selection',2012,'','','book'),('General dynamics of topology and traffic on weighted technological networks','APS','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),('Generalized inverses: theory and applications','Springer','not-in-selection',2003,'','','Book'),('Generalized multi-protocol label switching (GMPLS) architecture','tools.ietf','not-in-selection',2004,'','','journal'),('Generative growth model for power grids','IEEE','not-in-selection',2013,'','','proceedings'),('Geometry of complex networks and structural centrality','arXiv','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Globally networked risks and how to respond','nature','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Graph algorithms','CUP','not-in-selection',2011,'','','book'),('Handbook of Graphs \\& Networks','Wiley Online Library','not-in-selection',2002,'','','book'),('Heterogeneous bond percolation on multitype networks with an application to epidemic dynamics','APS','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Hierarchical organization of modularity in metabolic networks','AAAS','not-in-selection',2002,'','','journal'),('High-accuracy approximation of binary-state dynamics on networks','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('How scale-free are biological networks','Mary Ann Liebert','not-in-selection',2006,'','','journal'),('How to make a fragile network robust and vice versa','APS','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('How to model an internetwork','IEEE','not-in-selection',1996,'','','proceedings'),('How to ‘Glue’ a Robust Smart-Grid?','ACM','a22-ranjan',2011,'Smart-grids are made up of two interdependent constituents: a power production and distribution network catering to a geographic area and a communication network that helps regulate and control the power-grid from which it derives its electricity. Thus, failures in one of the two networks can lead to failures in the other and in some cases cause a cascade or domino effect, bringing down the entire system completely. In this work, we present a theoretical frame- work to model and study the structural properties of such interdependent networks based on a topological interpreta- tion [4] of the Moore-Penrose pseudo-inverse of the graph Laplacians (L+). Using this framework, we study how the way in which node pairs in two networks are coupled or “glued” together (thereby introducing interdependence) af- fects the overall robustness of the resulting interdependent networks. Our study leads to some surprising (and some- what counter-intuitive) results.','Begins explaining the importance of the study of interdependent networks. It wants to show and study: 1.how can we characterize the robustness of interdependent network on a whole? 2.how is the overall robustness of two interdependent networks affected by the manner in which the two networks are coupled together? 3.How do we judicially select an appropriate collection of coupled node pairs to introduce interdependence so that the resulting interdependent networks are more robust to random failures or targeted attacks?. Then it explains the mathematic tools to be used on their framework: the moore-penrose pseudo inverse and the kirchoff index and the interpretation they give to them. Then they present the model used to handle interdependent networks and test their framework. They conclude that for high coupling rate the most robust network is obtained by coupling the least central nodes while for low coupling an interdependent network that couples the most central nodes is more robust.','proceedings'),('Identification of influential spreaders in complex networks','nature','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),('Identification of k most vulnerable nodes in multi-layered network using a new model of interdependency','IEEE','not-in-selection',2014,'','','proceedings'),('Identifying influential nodes in complex networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),('Identifying, understanding, and analyzing critical infrastructure interdependencies','IEEE','not-in-selection',2001,'','','journal'),('ILOG CPLEX 12.0','ONLINE','not-in-selection',2011,'','','ONLINE'),('Impact of service network topology on air transportation efficiency','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('Impact of single links in competitive percolation','nature','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Improved El Ni{\\~n}o forecasting by cooperativity detection','NAS','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Improving interdependent networks robustness by adding connectivity links','ScienceDirect','Improving-interdependent',2015,'Compared with a single and isolated network, interdependent networks have two types of links: connectivity link and dependency link. This paper aims to improve the robustness of interdependent networks by adding connectivity links. Firstly, interdependent networks failure model and four frequently used link addition strategies are briefly reviewed. Furthermore, by defining inter degree–degree difference, two novel link addition strategies are proposed. Finally, we verify the effectiveness of our proposed link addition strategies by comparing with the current link addition strategies in three different network models. The simulation results show that, given the number of added links, link allocation strategies have great effects on the robustness of interdependent networks, i.e., the double-network link allocation strategy is superior to single-network link allocation strategy. Link addition strategies proposed in this paper excel the current strategies, especially for BA interdependent networks. Moreover, our work can provide guidance on how to allocate limited resources to an existing interdependent networks system and optimize its topology to avoid the potential cascade failures.','This paper explores the idea of adding connectivity links between nodes that weren\'t previously connected to improve the robustness of the overall system. It is assumed a \"one to one\" model with 2 interdependent networks of the same size and topological structure. The robustness is measured through g =(Na\'+Nb\')/(Na+Nb) [Na\' = largest connected component after failure on network A, Na= original size of network A] the relative size of the largest connected component. The failures used to test the system robustness were random and the amount of nodes to remove from network A are given by a fraction p (There\'s also pc the critical p where the system collapses). In this paper 4 existing ways of adding connectivity links are used and 2 are proposed, 1.- random addition, 2.-Low degree: pair 2 nodes with the lowest degrees, 3.-Low betweenness: pair 2 nodes with the lowest betweenness, 4 .-Algebraic connectivity based: on each step you select a pair of nodes with the maximum absolute difference between elements of the field vector connect them. Then they define the Inter Degree-Degree difference (IDD) as IDDab(u,v) =  K^a_u -  K^b_v where K^a_u is the degree of u in network A. They also introduce the Average IDD as Sum^N_i=1 |IDDi|/N. With this they following 2 strategies for adding connectivity links are presented. 5.- Low IDD: given one of the participating networks (A or B) add a link between a pair of nodes with the minimum IDD (ideally negative) 6.-Random IDD: pair 2 random nodes on the same networks with IDD < 0. For the test they used Scale-Free, Erdos-Renyi and Small world networks. They also determined how many links would be added through fa = (M\')/(Ma+Mb) (here fa=M\'/4000).','journal'),('Improving network robustness by edge modification','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),('Improving robustness of coupled networks against cascading failures','WorldScien.','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Improving the network robustness against cascading failures by adding links','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Inducing effect on the percolation transition in complex networks','nature','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Infection dynamics on scale-free networks','APS','not-in-selection',2001,'','','journal'),('Information cascades on degree-correlated random networks','APS','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Instability of scale-free networks under node-breaking avalanches','IOP','not-in-selection',2002,'','','journal'),('Inter-similarity between coupled networks','IOP','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Interacting epidemics on overlay networks','APS','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),('Interdependent networks with identical degrees of mutually dependent nodes','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Interdependent networks: reducing the coupling strength leads to a change from a first to second order percolation transition','APS','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),('Interdependent networks: vulnerability analysis and strategies to limit cascading failure','Springer','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('Interdependent Spatially Embedded Networks: Dynamics at Percolation Threshold','IEEE','6727251',2013,'Spatially embedded systems of interdependent net- works with full dependency (q = 1) have been found to have a first-order percolation transition if the dependency link length (the maximum distance in lattice units between a node in one network and the node that it depends on in another network) is longer than a certain critical length rc ≈ 8. We find here that a similar result is valid for any finite value of q with a larger rc as q decreases. We also provide a theoretical approach which correctly predicts the relationship between rc and q. We also examine the dynamics at the percolation threshold pc for varying r and q and find that there are three different mechanisms of failure for every q depending on r. Below rc the system undergoes a continuous transition similar to standard percolation. Above rc there are two distinct first-order transitions for finite or infinite r, respectively.The transition for finite r is characterized by spreading of node failures through the system while the infinite r corresponds to a non-spatial cascading failure similar to the case of random networks. These results extend previous results on spatially embedded interdependent networks to the more realistic cases of partial dependency and shed new light on the specific dynamics of cascading failures in such systems.','This paper studies the relation between the degree of dependece on intercontected network and the maximum length of the interdependent links for the network to have a second order transition (after this maximum length the network will have a first order percolation transtion/ an abrupt transition). To do so lattices were used to model the phenomena. Given q : dependency level, r_c : maximum interdependent link lenght before first order percolation transition, r : dependency link length. They look at the behaviour of the giant component (largest connected component) near the percolation threshold for different r values (0<r<r_c, r>= r_c, r = inf) and find relationships between them. They find that interdependent networks can avoid spreading catastrophic cascades only if the distance between interdependent nodes is below rc, though increasing the distance to a value much greater than rc can also provide a small increase in robustness with respect to random attacks.','proceedings'),('Introduction to percolation theory','CRC','not-in-selection',1994,'','','book'),('Is multilayer networking feasible?','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Jamming transition in air transportation networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Knowledge diffusion in the collaboration hypernetwork','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('Laplacian Eigenvectors of Graphs. Perron-Frobenius and Faber-Krahn Type Theorems,','Springer','not-in-selection',2007,'','','--'),('Laplacian matrices of graphs: a survey','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',1994,'','','journal'),('Laplacian of graphs and algebraic connectivity','IMPAS','not-in-selection',1989,'','','journal'),('Large scale structure and dynamics of complex networks: from information technology to finance and natural sciences','World Scien.','not-in-selection',2007,'','','book'),('Layered complex networks','APS','not-in-selection',2006,'','','journal'),('Layered percolation','arXiv','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('Leaders in social networks, the delicious case','PLS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Linear algebra and its applications','Pearson','not-in-selection',2005,'','','misc'),('Link overlap, viability, and mutual percolation in multiplex networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2015,'','','journal'),('Local search and the local structure of NP-complete problems','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',1992,'','','journal'),('Localized attacks on spatially embedded networks with dependencies','nature','srep08934',2015,'Many real world complex systems such as critical infrastructure networks are embedded in space and their components may depend on one another to function. They are also susceptible to geographically localized damage caused by malicious attacks or natural disasters. Here, we study a general model of spatially embedded networks with dependencies under localized attacks. We develop a theoretical and numerical approach to describe and predict the effects of localized attacks on spatially embedded systems with dependencies. Surprisingly, we find that a localized attack can cause substantially more damage than an equivalent random attack. Furthermore, we find that for a broad range of parameters, systems which appear stable are in fact metastable.Though robust to random failures—even of finite fraction—if subjected to a localized attack larger than a critical size which is independent of the system size (i.e., a zero fraction), a cascading failure emerges which leads to complete system collapse.','This paper proposes an approach to describe and predict the effects of localized attacks on spatially embedded systems with dependencies. To do so 2D \'diluted\' lattices with edge length constraints are considered to represent interdimentional networks. It is found that there are 3 possible states : stable, metastable, unestable when under \"local attacks\". A local attack is one that is centered on a node and affects nodes (destroys them) on a specific radius. Interdependent lattices are stable if under any radius of attack  (infinite) they don\'t collapse, metastable if under a certain attack radius is stable but above that radius it collapses and unestable if even a zero radius attacks makes the networks collapse. This work presents a complete analytical and simulation results to identify the interdependent lattice state. The results are in great concordance with the expected results from the analitycal part. IIt showed that local attacks bounded to \'physical\' radius can be catastrophic in a wide range of cases (interconected networks) while on a single lattice the local attack might not have an effect at all. ','journal'),('Managing disruption risks in supply chains','WOL','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),('Markov chains: Gibbs fields, Monte Carlo simulation, and queues','Springer','not-in-selection',2013,'','','book'),('Master-equation analysis of accelerating networks','APS','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Matcasc: A tool to analyse cascading line outages in power grids','IEEE','not-in-selection',2013,'','','proceedings'),('Measuring the cost of cybercrime','Springer','not-in-selection',2013,'','','book'),('Memory effect of the online user preference','nature','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('Mesh-based survivable networks: options and strategies for optical','MPLS','not-in-selection',2003,'','','journal'),('Minimizing Resource Protection in IP Over WDM Networks: Multi-layer Shared Backup Router [Invited]','IEEE','7063687',2015,'Optical networks and Internet Protocol/Multi- Protocol Label Switching (IP/MPLS) based networks have been traditionally designed and operated by separate de- partments of network operators. Likewise, both layers have always represented different business areas for sys- tem providers, which maintain different product lines for each of them. However, network operators have an IP/ MPLS over WDM architecture. The main drivers for this unique transport network are the cost savings achieved by simplifying the network infrastructure. Thanks to the advent of reconfigurable optical equipment and a multi- layer control plane, 1  1 node protection at the IP layer in each location is no longer required. This work compares two resilience strategies on multi-layer network dimen- sioning: dual-plane protection and a multi-layer shared backup router (MLSBR). Based on the results of this paper, a MLSBR provides a significant reduction (up to 24%) on the required IP equipment in comparison with the IP pro- tection approach.','This paper focuses on the analisis of real communication networks. To analize the resilience of a network they use the \'Availability\' metric which measures how “survivable” a network is, the availability concept is defined as how long (how much time) a user can access to the services provided by the network. They analize the Availavility of the \'Core Telefónica Spanish Network\' under their proposed MLSBR strategy. The work showed the higher availability of this mechanism in comparison with the current dual-plane protection scheme. The analytical study is done using Markov’s chain model where the node reachability status is defined accordingly.','journal'),('Mitigation of cascading failures on complex networks','Springer','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),('Mitigation of malicious attacks on networks','NAS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Mitigation strategies on scale-free networks against cascading failures','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Model for cascading failures in complex networks','APS','not-in-selection',2004,'','','journal'),('Modeling cascading failures in the North American power grid',