hs I','','not-in-selection',1959,'','','journal'),('On the dynamics of cascading failures in interdependent networks','arXiv','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),('On the evolution of random graphs','PMIHAS','not-in-selection',1960,'','','journal'),('On the placement of infrastructure overlay nodes','IEEE','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('On the robustness of Spanish telecommunication networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),('Onion-like network topology enhances robustness against malicious attacks','IOP','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Onset of cooperation between layered networks','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Optimal allocation of interconnecting links in cyber-physical systems: Interdependence, cascading failures, and robustness','IEEE','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),('Optimal dynamic bandwidth allocation for complex networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Optimal intentional islanding to enhance the robustness of power grid networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Optimal path in random networks with disorder: A mini review','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),('Optimal weighting scheme and the role of coupling strength against load failures in degree-based weighted interdependent networks','ScienceDirect','Optimal-weighting',2013,'The optimal weighting scheme and the role of coupling strength against load failures on symmetrically and asymmetrically coupled interdependent networks were investigated. The degree-based weighting scheme was extended to interdependent networks, with the flow dynamics dominated by global redistribution based on weighted betweenness centrality. Through contingency analysis of one-node removal, we demonstrated that there still exists an optimal weighting parameter on interdependent networks, but it might shift as compared to the case in isolated networks because of the break of symmetry. And it will be easier for the symmetrically and asymmetrically coupled interdependent networks to achieve robustness and better cost configuration against the one-node-removal-induced cascade of load failures when coupling strength was weaker. Our findings might have great generality for characterizing load-failure-induced cascading dynamics in real-world degree-based weighted interdependent networks.','This paper studies de Global load-based redistribution by assigning the load through intra-degree and inter-degree properties. The robustness is measured by removing each node once and re-adjusting the capacities of the nodes to take the load of the one node removal without falling apart. Then the investment of the initial network is compared with the invesment of the adjusted network. With this the optimal weighting parameter (thetha*) is the one resulting in the minimum investment (I1*). They define the adjustment ratio R = I1/I0, the smaller the ratio, the easier it is for the network to gain robustness against one-node removal from the initial configuration. The tests are performed over Scale-Free and Erdos-Renyi networks with symetrical coupling [N=Na=Nb=100, <k>=<ka>=<kb>=4, <¨ka>=<¨kb>=<¨k>=2], and asymmetrical coupling [Na=50, Nb=100, <k>=<ka>=<kb>=6, <¨ka>=4,<¨kb>=2].','journal'),('Optimal weighting scheme for suppressing cascades and traffic congestion in complex networks','APS','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Optimization of network robustness to random breakdowns','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2006,'','','journal'),('Optimization of network robustness to waves of targeted and random attacks','APS','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),('Optimization of robustness and connectivity in complex networks','APS','not-in-selection',2003,'','','journal'),('Optimization of robustness of complex networks','Springer','not-in-selection',2004,'','','journal'),('Optimization of robustness of scale-free network to random and targeted attacks','WorldScien.','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),('Optimizing algebraic connectivity by edge rewiring','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Optimizing complex networks for resilience against cascading failure','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2007,'','','journal'),('Optimizing network topology for cascade resilience','Springer','not-in-selection',2012,'','','collection'),('Organization of modular networks','APS','not-in-selection',2008,'','','journal'),('Organizations of rich nodes in complex networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2007,'','','journal'),('Origins of fractality in the growth of complex networks','nature','not-in-selection',2006,'','','journal'),('Path diversity improves the identification of influential spreaders','IOP','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('Percolation and conduction','APS','not-in-selection',1973,'','','journal'),('Percolation and epidemics in random clustered networks','APS','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Percolation in interdependent and interconnected networks: Abrupt change from second-to first-order transitions','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Percolation in multiplex networks with overlap','APS','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Percolation in networks composed of connectivity and dependency links','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Percolation in networks of networks with random matching of nodes in different layers','arXiv','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('Percolation in real interdependent networks','nature','nphys3374',2015,'The function of a real network depends not only on the reliability of its own components, but is affected also by the simultaneous operation of other real networks coupled with it. Whereas theoretical methods of direct applicability to real isolated networks exist, the frameworks developed so far in percolation theory for interdependent network layers are of little help in practical contexts, as they are suited only for special models in the limit of infinite size. Here, we introduce a set of heuristic equations that takes as inputs the adjacency matrices of the layers to draw the entire phase diagram for the interconnected network. We demonstrate that percolation transitions in interdependent networks can be understood by decomposing these systems into uncoupled graphs: the intersection among the layers, and the remainders of the layers. When the intersection dominates the remainders, an interconnected network undergoes a smooth percolation transition. Conversely, if the intersection is dominated by the contribution of the remainders, the transition becomes abrupt even in small networks. We provide examples of real systems that have developed interdependent networks sharing cores of ‘high quality’ edges to prevent catastrophic failures.','This paper proposes a method to satudy the percolation thresholds of complex coupled networks. It recognizes problems on the assumptions of previous model (the graph models topology is not specified by a one-zero adjacency matrix, they\'re applied to infinitely large systems) that real interconnected networks don\'t possess. Then a methodology to describe percolation transitions is explained. By defining several concepts and steps the paper arrives to an euristic equation for the probability that a node i is in the largest mutually connected cluster of the system. They determine that the percolation transition depends on size of the intersection of the graph vs the remainder. The method is tested by comparing empyrical results against the theoretical results obtained from the heuristic equation. One thing apreciated is that in heterogeneous graphs the nature of transition is not determined by the number of edges shared across the layers but their quality. The results of the theoretical and empyrical results are very similar concluding that the framework is able to help identify cores of quality links that can prevent catastrophic failures in real systems.','journal'),('Percolation in self-similar networks','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Percolation of a general network of networks','APS','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Percolation of interdependent networks with intersimilarity','APS','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Percolation of localized attack on complex networks','IOP','not-in-selection',2015,'','','journal'),('Percolation of partially interdependent networks under targeted attack','APS','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),('Percolation of partially interdependent scale-free networks','APS','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Percolation on dense graph sequences','IMS','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),('Percolation on interacting networks','arXiv','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Percolation on interacting, antagonistic networks','IOP','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Percolation on sparse networks','APS','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('Percolation theory applied to measures of fragmentation in social networks','APS','not-in-selection',2007,'','','journal'),('Percolation theory on interdependent networks based on epidemic spreading','IOP','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),('Percolation transitions are not always sharpened by making networks interdependent','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Performance analysis of complex networks and systems','CUP','not-in-selection',2014,'','','book'),('Performance and reliability of electrical power grids under cascading failures','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Perspectives on risk management in supply chains','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('PlanetLab project','ONLINE','not-in-selection',2030,'','','ONLINE'),('Power-law distributions in empirical data','SIAM','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Preferential attachment in the interaction between dynamically generated interdependent networks','IOP','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),('Proactive robustness control of heterogeneously loaded networks','APS','not-in-selection',2006,'','','journal'),('Probabilistic study of cascading failures in complex interdependent lifeline systems','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Promoting collective motion of self-propelled agents by distance-based influence','APS','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('Protecting infrastructure networks from cost-based attacks','IOP','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('QoSMap: achieving quality and resilience through overlay construction','IEEE','not-in-selection',2009,'','','proceedings'),('QoSMap: QoS aware mapping of virtual networks for resiliency and efficiency','IEEE','not-in-selection',2007,'','','proceedings'),('Random Graphs','Springer','not-in-selection',1985,'','','journal'),('Random graphs containing arbitrary distributions of subgraphs','APS','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),('Random graphs with arbitrary degree distributions and their applications','APS','not-in-selection',2001,'','','journal'),('Random graphs with clustering','APS','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Random walks on complex networks','APS','not-in-selection',2004,'','','journal'),('Reaction--diffusion processes and metapopulation models in heterogeneous networks','nature','not-in-selection',2007,'','','journal'),('Recent development on supply chain supernetwork modeling','Shanghai.LD','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Recovering from disruptions of interdependent critical infrastructures','-','not-in-selection',2001,'','','proceedings'),('Recovery from malicious transactions','IEEE','not-in-selection',2002,'','','journal'),('Reflection on supernetwork','Shanghai.LD','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Reliability Analysis of Interdependent Networks Using Percolation Theory','IEEE','6727252',2013,'Many complex systems have functional interde- pendency between each other and can be modeled as interdepen- dent networks. The failure of a small fraction of nodes in inter- dependent networks may lead to catastrophic cascading failures across network borders. Starting from a model of static interde- pendent networks, by introducing lifetime for each component, we study the reliability properties and lifetimes of the interde- pendent networks to which these components belong. Depending on the lifetime of the network components, the trigger of cascad- ing failures will shape the interdependent networks reliability. In this framework, we analyze the evolution of the reliability prop- erties of interdependent networks, and compare them with single networks. Interdependent SF networks are found to have lower reliability than interdependent ER networks.','The main objective of this work is to study the reliabilty of a network and its overall \'lifetime\' given that each component have its own lifetime after which the components begin to fail an collapse. They use the one to one model of dependency and for simplicity they couple networks that have the same amount of nodes. With the lifetime and reliability studies \'size of the largest connected component\' are also analyzed. Comparisons between single networks and interconnected networks with components with lifetime are performed. Overall lifetime versus average component lifetime and standar deviation lifetime as well as degradation or reliability over time are performed. It is found that the lifetime of interconnected networks is significantly shorter than the lifetime of single networks under the same conditions, SF (scale-free) networks presents an inferior reliability versus ER (erdos-renyi) networks and that due the combined effect of structure and time the network lifetime decreases with standard deviation of component life distribution, while the lifetime of the single network increases with the standard deviation of the component life distribution.','proceedings'),('Reliability engineering','JohnWiley&Sons','not-in-selection',2012,'','','book'),('Renormalization group analysis of the small-world network model','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',1999,'','','journal'),('Resilience in multilayer networks','IEEE','not-in-selection',1999,'','','journal'),('Resilience of complex networks to random breakdown','APS','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),('Resilience of the internet to random breakdowns','APS','not-in-selection',2000,'','','journal'),('Resilient multilayer traffic engineering through dynamic path restoration','Citeseer','not-in-selection',2004,'','','proceedings'),('Resilient overlay networks','ACM','not-in-selection',2001,'','','proceedings'),('Revealing the process of edge-based-attack cascading failures','Springer','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),('Review on modeling and simulation of interdependent critical infrastructure systems','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('Robust allocation of weighted dependency links in cyber–physical networks','ScienceDirect','Robust-allocation',2015,'Interdependent network models are often used to show how one network has an effect on another network through dependencies. In this paper, we propose a novel interdependent network model which consists of two individual networks with unequal numbers of nodes and one-to-multiple weighted dependency links between the two networks. Based on realistic assumptions, this model differs from previous works that considered equal numbers of nodes in the two networks and identical dependency links. We formulate an optimization problem to allocate dependency links using least resources. This novel model enhances the practicability of traditional cyber–physical system structures, but it makes the dependency link deployment problem more complex and the optimization problem cannot be solved in large networks. To overcome this problem, we propose a new algorithm based on a revised network flow method. Extensive simulations on random networks and real networks show that our deployment method produces topologies that are more robust than the ones obtained by other deployment techniques. Results indicate that our algorithm is efficient and cost-effective in designing robust interdependent networks, and our deployment method is suitable for networks of any size.','This paper tackles the problem of allocating links (dependency links that connect 2 different networks in particular) given that each one have a cost and there\'s a budget (a limit to the amount of link you can afford). Here, as in other papers, the biggest connected component is the one that\'s considered functional. However they propose a one-to-multiple dependence over networks that are no neccesarily the same one or have the same amount of nodes (Although for simulation pourposes they couple networks with the same \"structure\"). For a node to properly function it has to be connected to the largest connected component and have at least one dependency link. The robustness metric they use is the average value of the size of the largest connected component divided by the original size of the network for each network. The allocation process is divided on 2 steps. The first one is Basic connectivity to ensure that every node has at least one dependency link (you need max(Na,Nb) links). The second step is the augmented connectivity, here the remaining budget is use according to some strategy. The authors say that \"the aim of augmented connectivity is to achieve minimum variance of node degree\" (for better robustness). To perform the tests they use 2 strategies \"maximize the number of dependencies\" and \"random\" on ER networks coupled (they did not use the same network, they have differen sizes Nb=(1+a)Na).','journal'),('Robust-yet-fragile nature of interdependent networks','APS','not-in-selection',2015,'','','journal'),('Robustness analysis of static routing on networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Robustness envelopes of networks','Oxford Un.','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Robustness in simple biochemical networks','nature','not-in-selection',1997,'','','journal'),('Robustness measure for power grids with respect to cascading failures','ITC','not-in-selection',2011,'','','proceedings'),('Robustness of a network formed by n interdependent networks with a one-to-one correspondence of dependent nodes','APS','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),('Robustness of a network of networks','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Robustness of a partially interdependent network formed of clustered networks','APS','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('Robustness of complex networks with the local protection strategy against cascading failures','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Robustness of interdependent and interconnected clustered networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('Robustness of interdependent networks under several intentional attack strategies','Shanghai.LD','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),('Robustness of interdependent networks under targeted attack','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Robustness of Interdependent Networks: The case of communication networks and the power grid','IEEE','6831395',2013,'We study the robustness of interdependent networks, in which the state of one network depends on the state of the other network and vice versa. In particular, we focus on the interdependency between the power grid and communication networks, where the grid depends on communications for its control, and the communication network depends on the grid for power. A real-world example is the Italian blackout of 2003, when a small failure in the power grid cascaded between the two networks and led to a massive blackout. In this paper, we study the minimum number of node failures needed to cause total blackout (i.e., all nodes in both networks to fail).In the case of unidirectional interdependency between the networks we show that the problem is NP-hard, and develop heuristics to find a near-optimal solution. On the other hand, we show that in the case of bidirectional interdependency this problem can be solved in polynomial time. We believe that this new interdependency model gives rise to important, yet unexplored, robust network design problems for interdependent networked infrastructures.','In this paper the authors analyze the robustness of interdependent networks where the interdependencies are manifested 2 ways. For each way they want to know the minimum number of node failures needed to cause total blackout. They focus on the example of SCADA-Power grid dependencies. The first case considered is the unidirectional dependency case where if a router node depends on a certain power node it doesn\'t mean that power node depends on that router node. The second case is the one to one dependency where if one of the coupled nodes fails the other fails as well. The former case is proven to be an NP-complete problem so heuristics to tackle it are given, while the latter case is a polynomial problem. The tests are performed over star like networks to measure the effects of the interdependencies on the cascading failures and those effects only (star like means that, for ex., on the power grid every node is connected to the generator and generators can function by themselves). With this last assumption the coupled networks can be seen as bipartite graphs. They found that the network of Italy is robust to total failure. However, they showed that parts of the network are very vulnerable to failures. The robustness metric used is the minimun number of nodes that must be removed for total collapse.','proceedings'),('Robustness of multilayer oscillator networks','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Robustness of n interdependent networks with partial support-dependence relationship','IOP','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(