ecies','NAS','not-in-selection',2006,'','','journal'),('Self-similarity of complex networks','nature','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),('Service overlay networks: SLAs, QoS, and bandwidth provisioning','IEEE','not-in-selection',2003,'','','journal'),('Shared backup router resources: realizing virtualized network resilience','IEEE','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Small Cluster in Cyber Physical Systems: Network Topology, Interdependence and Cascading Failures','IEEE','6863675',2015,'In cyber physical system (CPS), computational resources and physical resources are strongly correlated and mutually dependent. Cascading failures occur between coupled networks, cause the system more fragile than single network. Besides widely used metric giant component, we study small cluster (small component) in interdependent networks after cascading failures occur. We first introduce an overview on how small clusters distribute in various single networks. Then we propose a percolation theory based mathematical method to study how small clusters be affected by the interdependence between two coupled networks. We prove that the upper bounds exist for both the fraction and the number of operating small clusters. Without loss of generality, we apply both synthetic network and real network data in simulation to study small clusters under different interdependence models and network topologies. The extensive simulations highlight our findings: except the giant component, considerable proportion of small clusters exists, with the remaining part fragmenting to very tiny pieces or even massive isolated single vertex; no matter how the two networks are tightly coupled, an upper bound exists for the size of small clusters. We also discover that the interdependent small-world networks generally have the highest fractions of operating small clusters. Three attack strategies are compared: Inter Degree Priority Attack, Intra Degree Priority Attack and Random Attack. We observe that the fraction of functioning small clusters keeps stable and is independent from the attack strategies.','Here a different view on the robustness measurements is shown. The authors say that measuring the largest connected component and assuming that a node that\'s not connected to it is non operational is wrong. Instead they propose to take into account the amount of small clusters that remain functional after an attack. A node remains operational if it is connected to a cluster with a minimum size delta and it is interconnected. They also propose an alternative to the one to one coupling that they call \"k-n\", in this coupling they have unidirectional links and two types of nodes (one connects with k other nodes, the other with n). They show that the semaller the delta the more robust is the network. And that it is necessary to take small clusters (that are functional) into account in order to properly evaluate network robustness.','journal'),('Small worlds: the dynamics of networks between order and randomness','PUP','not-in-selection',1999,'','','book'),('Smart grid communications and networking','CUP','not-in-selection',2012,'','','book'),('Spatial networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Spatially localized attacks on interdependent networks: the existence of a finite critical attack size','arXiv','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Spectra of random graphs with given expected degrees','NAS','not-in-selection',2003,'','','journal'),('Spectral graph theory','AMS','not-in-selection',1997,'','','book'),('Spectral measure of structural robustness in complex networks','IEEE','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Spectral redemption in clustering sparse networks','NAS','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Spin glass theory and beyond.','WSP','not-in-selection',1990,'','','journal'),('Spontaneous recovery in dynamical networks','nature','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('Spread of epidemic disease on networks','APS','not-in-selection',2002,'','','journal'),('Spreading dynamics in complex networks','IOP','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Spreading of cooperative behaviour across interdependent groups','nature','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Stability and topology of scale-free networks under attack and defense strategies','APS','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),('Statistical mechanics of complex networks','APS','not-in-selection',2002,'','','journal'),('Statistical physics of social dynamics','APS','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Structural vulnerability of power systems: A topological approach','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Structural vulnerability of the North American power grid','APS','not-in-selection',2004,'','','journal'),('Structure of shells in complex networks','APS','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Study of the Use of a Genetic Algorithm to Improve Networked System-of-Systems Resilience','ScienceDirect','Study-of-the-use',2014,'Large scale failures or degradation resulting from smaller initial failures or disruptions in networked system-of- systems are an issue in multiple areas - for example cascading failures in electrical power grids or large disruptions in national air traffic due to local or regional weather conditions. The system architecture can have a significant impact on system-of-systems susceptibility to large scale failures. /The study presented in this paper uses a simple interdependent networked system-of-systems failure model, integrated into a unique objective function that addresses both the overall level of failure and the rate of failure progression, and a genetic algorithm to demonstrate an integrated failure modeling based optimization method to select system-of-systems architectures for improved resiliency. /The results for the integrated failure model/genetic algorithm model results converged rapidly to a steady state values. This initial integration shows a possible path forward to more sophisticated model integration and optimization and demonstrates a basic level of feasibility for this general approach.','This paper proposes a genetic algorithm to optimize the robustness of networks against failures. The model is based on 2 interdependent grid type networks of dimension Xi x Yi and Xj x Yj. For the experiments each network has 2500 nodes. The interactions between the networks are unidirectional, that is, the failure propagates to the other network only if in the original network fails a node such that a node in the other network depended on it.  For the algorithm attacks are used, these attacks strike an area of the network defined by a radius and center. The nodes that fail become \"inactive\". This paper measures the extent of the fully developed failure region and the speed of the cascading process to measure the robustness of the network. Here interdependence intra-network are not taken into consideration. Attacks were performed at random.','journal'),('Stuxnet under the microscope','ESET LLC','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),('Successful strategies for competing networks','nature','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Sudden emergence of a giantk-core in a random graph','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',1996,'','','journal'),('Supercooled and glassy water','IOP','not-in-selection',2003,'','','journal'),('Supply chain supernetworks and environmental criteria','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2003,'','','journal'),('Suppressing cascades of load in interdependent networks','NAS','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),('Survivability of multiple fiber duct failures','researchgate','not-in-selection',2001,'','','proceedings'),('Survivable IP/MPLS-over-WSON multilayer network optimization','OSA','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Survivable paths in multilayer networks','IEEE','not-in-selection',2012,'','','proceedings'),('Survivable routing of mesh topologies in IP-over-WDM networks by recursive graph contraction','IEEE','not-in-selection',2007,'','','journal'),('Sustainable fashion supply chain management under oligopolistic competition and brand differentiation','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),('Synchronization in interdependent networks','AIP','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Temporal networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),('The anatomy of a large-scale hypertextual web search engine','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',1998,'','','journal'),('The art of computer programming, volume 2','Addison-Wesley','not-in-selection',1997,'','','book'),('The art of computer programming: sorting and searching','Pearson','not-in-selection',1998,'','','book'),('The combined effect of connectivity and dependency links on percolation of networks','Springer','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('The effect of attack cost on network robustness','IOP','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('The effect of clustering-based and degree-based weighting on robustness in symmetrically coupled heterogeneous interdependent networks','IEEE','6722433',2013,'We studied robustness of symmetrically coupled interdependent networks against load failures when the flow dynamics is dominated by global redistribution based on weighted betweenness centrality. Three kinds of weighting schemes, which are random, clustering-based, and degree-based, respectively, were compared. We demonstrated that both the clustering-based and degree-based weighting scheme outweigh random weighting on robustness against the cascade of load failures in the symmet- rically coupled interdependent networks. In a limited range of weighting parameters, degree-based weighting scheme outweigh clustering-based scheme. Outside of that range, clustering-based weighting scheme outweigh degree-based scheme. And it will be easier for the symmetrically coupled interdependent network to achieve robustness against one-node removal and better cost configuration against the cascade of load failures when relative interconnection intensity was weaker under degree-based and clustering-based weighting schemes. Our findings might have great generality for characterizing load-failure-induced cascading dynamics in real-world weighted interdependent networks.','The paper is centered on the proposal and testing of different ways of assigning weight to links on interdependent networks. This weights are used to determine how to redistribute the load of the network in case that occurs a node failure. This last point is important to avoid further cascading failures (intra and inter networks) due to excesive load. In this paper the weighting idea is extended to interconnected networks, the weighting strategies are extended as well (betweennes, degree, clustering). Here the cost of the weighting is also studied. A network would be considered \"more robust\" if for it is \'easier\' to gain robustness (cost wise).','proceedings'),('The effect of interdependence on the percolation of interdependent networks','ScienceDirect','The-effect-of',2014,'Two stochastic models are proposed to generate a system composed of two interdependent scale-free (SF) or ErdÆs–Rényi (ER) networks where interdependent nodes are connected with an exponential or power-law relation, as well as different dependence strength, respectively. Each subnetwork grows through the addition of new nodes with constant accelerating random attachment in the first model but with preferential attachment in the second model. The two subnetworks interact with multi-support and undirectional dependence links. The effects of dependence relations and strength between subnetworks are analyzed in the percolation behavior of fully interdependent networks against random failure, both theoretically and numerically, and as a result, for both relations: interdependent SF networks show a second-order percolation phase transition and the increased dependence strength decreases the robustness of the system, whereas, interdependent ER networks show the opposite results. In addition, the power-law relation between networks yields greater robustness than the exponential one at the given dependence strength.','In this paper they present a simple framework but with 2 different models possible. To resume: once the network is modeled they test the resilience by measuring the percolation threshold for each initial p. The models are constructed on steps where nodes and links are added. There are two types of links: connectivity links (intra) and dependency links (inter). The first model begins with m0 nodes and n0 connectivity links on each network (A and B), on each step t it add a node to every network. Each node in A adds mA links, it attaches itself with a 1-qa fraction of nodes in the same network through connectivity links. The rest of the links are dependency links who are attached to nodes in B. (For each node in B is the same). The second model is initiated in the same way but when the nodes are added on each network and on each step t the link addition it\'s done by the constant acceleration scenario. Given the new node in A, this scenario adds a connectivity link between 2 nodes in A with probability s, it must be satisfied that the expected amount of links is st. In the case of the addition of dependency links they can be added at random or preferentially (DL) (exponenctial dependence-degree dist or power-law-degree dist.).  This second model ends up creating a ER network with poisson degree distribution. The tests performed study the percolation threshold pc for different q (level of dependence), and the sizes of the largest connected components depending on p (the cascading process begins by removing 1-p nodes from network A). A node is considered functional if it belongs to the largest connected component and has at leats 1 dependency link. With the tests theoretycal predictions were shown and both test results and prediction results were contrasted.','journal'),('The evolution of random graphs','','not-in-selection',1960,'','','journal'),('The extreme vulnerability of interdependent spatially embedded networks','nature','nphys2727',2013,'Recent studies show that in interdependent networks a very small failure in one network may lead to catastrophic consequences. Above a critical fraction of interdependent nodes, even a single node failure can invoke cascading failures that may abruptly fragment the system, whereas below this critical dependency a failure of a few nodes leads only to a small amount of damage to the system. So far, research has focused on interdependent random networks without space limitations. However, many real systems, such as power grids and the Internet, are not random but are spatially embedded. Here we analytically and numerically study the stability of interdependent spatially embedded networks modelled as lattice networks. Surprisingly, we find that in lattice systems, in contrast to non-embedded systems, there is no critical dependency and any small fraction of interdependent nodes leads to an abrupt collapse. We show that this extreme vulnerability of very weakly coupled lattices is a consequence of the critical exponent describing the percolation transition of a single lattice.','The paper begins explaining that not all networks are random and that in many cases these are spatially embedded. In order to study the effects of this kind of structure they use percolation theory and lattice graphs, though they acknowlodge that most of these networks are not lattices. In this paper they show the theory using interdependent networks composed by two networks. It is focused on the case where both networks have the same degree distribution. With this they proceed to analyze the size of the giant component at criticality in function of the coupling strenght q, for this, they used different simulated and real networks coupled together. It concludes that for spatially embedded networks even a weak coupling lead to a relatively large-scale collapse while for random networks the discontinuity size does not have a singular point. In the case of lattice-RR (Random Regular) the singularity is slightly weaker than the lattice-lattice case.','journal'),('The fractal nature of a diffusion front and the relation to percolation','LesEditionsP','not-in-selection',1985,'','','journal'),('The igraph software package for complex network research','InterJournal','not-in-selection',2006,'','','journal'),('The impact of supply chain integration on the “snowball effect” in the transmission of disruptions: An empirical evaluation of the model','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('The impact of the topology on cascading failures in a power grid model','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('The interaction between multiplex community networks','AIP','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('The power grid as a complex network: a survey','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('The resilience of WDM networks to probabilistic geographical failures','IEEE','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('The resilient enterprise: overcoming vulnerability for competitive advantage','MITPress','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),('The robustness and restoration of a network of ecological networks','AAAS','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),('The robustness of interdependent clustered networks','IOP','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('The robustness of interdependent transportation networks under targeted attack','IOP','not-in-selection',2013,'','','39'),('The role of the airline transportation network in the prediction and predictability of global epidemics','NAS','not-in-selection',2006,'','','journal'),('The severity of supply chain disruptions: design characteristics and mitigation capabilities','WOL','not-in-selection',2007,'','','journal'),('The structure and dynamics of multilayer networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('The Structure and Dynamics of Networks','PUP','not-in-selection',2006,'','','journal'),('The structure and function of complex networks','SIAM','not-in-selection',2003,'','','journal'),('The topological and electrical structure of power grids','IEEE','not-in-selection',2010,'','','proceedings'),('The unreasonable effectiveness of tree-based theory for networks with clustering','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('The worldwide air transportation network: Anomalous centrality, community structure, and cities\' global roles','NAS','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),('Theoretical approaches to node assignment','Uni.Cargn','not-in-selection',2002,'','','journal'),('Tight lower bound for percolation threshold on an infinite graph','APS','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),('Tolerance of scale-free networks against attack-induced cascades','APS','not-in-selection',2005,'','','451'),('Toward self-healing energy infrastructure systems','IEEE','not-in-selection',2001,'','','journal'),('Towards design principles for optimal transport networks','APS','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),('Towards designing robust coupled networks','nature','srep01969',2013,'Natural and technological interdependent systems have been shown to be highly vulnerable due to cascading failures and an abrupt collapse of global connectivity under initial failure. Mitigating the risk by partial disconnection endangers their functionality. Here we propose a systematic strategy of selecting a minimum number of autonomous nodes that guarantee a smooth transition in robustness. Our method which is based on betweenness is tested on various examples including the famous 2003 electrical blackout of Italy. We show that, with this strategy, the necessary number of autonomous nodes can be reduced by a factor of five compared to a random choice. We also find that the transition to abrupt collapse follows tricritical scaling characterized by a set of exponents which is independent on the protection strategy.','This paper focuses on the problem of decoupling nodes in order to make a more robust network. A methodology to choose specific nodes by a certain criteria, in this case centrality measures, is presented. The robustness of the coupled networks is studied through an extension of the R-index for more than one layer. It\'s demonstrated that by decoupling nodes by the criteria is possible to change the percolation transition from a discontinuous (catastrophic) to a smooth one. Also by using certain critera instead of choosing random it is possible to reduce the amount of nodes to decouple in order to make the networks more robust.  ','journal'),('Transient dynamics increasing network vulnerability to cascading failures','APS','not-in-selection',2008,'','','journal'),('Transport in networks with multiple sources and sinks','IOP','not-in-selection',2008,'','','journal'),('Transport on coupled spatial networks','APS','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),('Tricritical exponents and scaling fields','APS','not-in-selection',1972,'','','journal'),('Tricritical point in explosive percolation','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Uber quadratische Formen mit reellen Koeffizienten','Springer','not-in-selection',1905,'','','journal'),('Uberber die Eigenwerte bei den Differentialgleichungen der mathematischen Physik','Springer','not-in-selection',1920,'','','journal'),('Ultra high capacity optical transmission networks: Final report of action cost 239','UZagreb','not-in-selection',1999,'','','journal'),('Unavailability of critical SCADA communication links interconnecting a power grid and a telco network','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),('Understanding the cascading failures in Indian power grids with complex networks theory','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),('Universal behavior of load distribution in scale-free networks','APS','not-in-selection',2001,'','','journal'),('Universal robustness characteristic of weighted networks against cascading failure','APS','not-in-selection',2008,'','','journal'),('Usefulness of DC power flow for active power flow analysis with flow controlling devices','IET','not-in-selection',2006,'','','proceedings'),('Vertex overload breakdown in evolving networks','APS','not-in-selection',2002,'','','journal'),('Virtual network embedding through topology-aware node ranking','ACM','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),('Virtual network embedding with coordinated node and link mapping','IEEE','not-in-selection',2009,'','','proceedings'),('Virus spread in networks','IEEE','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),('Vulnerability of state-interdependent networks under malware spreading','ScienceDirect','Vulneravility-of-state',2014,'Computer viruses are evolving by developing spreading mechanisms based on the use of multiple vectors of propagation. The use of the social network as an extra vector of attack to penetrate the security measures in IP networks is improving the effectiveness of malware, and have therefore been used by the most aggressive viruses, like Conficker and Stuxnet. In this work we use interdependent networks to model the propagation of these kind of viruses. In particular, we study the propagation of a SIS model on interdependent networks where the state of each node is layer-independent and the dynamics in each network follows either a contact process or a reactive process, with different propagation rates. We apply this study to the case of existing interdependent networks, namely a Spanish scientific community of Statistical Physics, formed by a social network of scientific collaborations and a physical network of connected computers in each institution. We show that the interplay between layers increases dramatically the infectivity of viruses in the long term and their robustness against immunization.','The paper studies contagion dynamics, they take the particular case of the malware contagion. This paper develops a new formalism that applies to the study of the epidemic spreading in these kind of systems. The idea is to take into account the contagion process. They show the concept of state-interdependent networks (SINs). This is a multi-layered network where on each network there\'s the same amount of nodes and each node has the same id on each network, here there are no links between layers, instead the nodes with the same id share the same \'\'state\'\'. In this paper the states are given by a SIS epidemic model (Infected, susceptible). On this model each layer exhibits a different contagion pattern. The contagion patern is measured over time considering the probability of get infected or the probability of recovery. The robustness of the network is measured through the density of infected nodes. They test their proposal using the Spanish Statistical Physics networks, 2 layers are defined: physical and social. On each layer the authors are nodes. On the physical layer the links represent that they belong to the same university and department or that they belong to the same research center. On the social network the links represent collaboration between authors. The experiments were averaged over 200 realizations and they all start with the network fully infected. The results show that the dynamics of the SIS contagion proces in SINs where the states of the nodes must be layer-independent is equivalent to the spreading in a mono-layer governed by the effective contagion.','journal'),('W32. stuxnet dossier','whitepaper symantec','not-in-selection',2011,'','','whitepaper'),('What energy functions can be minimized via graph cuts?','IEEE','not-in-selection',2004,'','','journal'),('￼Complex interdependent supply chain networks: Cascading failure and robustness','ScienceDirect','Complex-interdependent',2015,'A supply chain network is a typical interdependent network composed of an undirected cyber-layer network and a directed physical-layer network. To analyze the robustness of this complex interdependent supply chain network when it suffers from disruption events that can cause nodes to fail, we use a cascading failure process that focuses on load propagation. We consider load propagation via connectivity links as node failure spreads through one layer of an interdependent network, and we develop a priority redistribution strategy for failed loads subject to flow constraint. Using a giant component function and a one-to-one directed interdependence relation between nodes in a cyber-layer network and physical-layer network, we construct time-varied functional equations to quantify the dynamic process of failed loads propagation in an interdependent network. Finally, we conduct a numerical simulation for two cases, i.e., single node removal and multiple node removal at the initial disruption. The simulation results show that when we increase the number of removed nodes in an interdependent supply chain network its robustness undergoes a first-order discontinuous phase transition, and that even removing a small number of nodes will cause it to crash.','This paper propos a model for interdependent supply chain network composed by a physical network and a logical network. Each network is slightly different, but both have load capacities on its nodes and edges and the same amount of nodes. The physical network is a directed network representing the physical supply chain (suppliers, manufacterers, etc.) and logical network is a non directed graph. In this framework the model presented follows a one to one relation in the sense that a node in one network is conected to only one node on the other network, these dependencies may be uni or bidirectional. Nodes may fail due to attacks or overloads. A node is considered functional if it belongs to the largest connected component and survives the cascading failures, the rest of the nodes that survive but don\'t belong to the largest connected component are considered partially functional. They tested the robustness of the interdependent supply chain network by removing 1 node on the logical network or a fraction 1-p of it, 1 node on the physical network or a fraction 1-p of it and a fraction 1-p between the 2 networks. The tests performed tunned the parameter of the networks (load capacities) to study the supply chain. On the case of removing a fraction 1-p of nodes these were chosen at random, on descending degree order an on ascending degree order. The comprehensive efficiency index was used to measure robustness as well as transition order studies. On the model the redistribution of loads towards other nodes is given by a probabilty.','journal'),('￼Robustness of interdependent networks with different link patterns against cascading failures','ScienceDirect','Robustness-of-interdependent',2013,'Taking into account the load, the load redistribution, and the node capacity, we study the robustness of two interdependent networks A and B against cascading failures, where each node in network A depends on one node in network B, and vice versa. We adopt three kinds of link patterns between two interdependent networks, i.e., the assortative link (AL), the disassortative link (DL), the random link (RL), where the RA refers to connect randomly two nodes in networks A and B, the AL refers to that high-degree (low-degree) nodes in A network link high-degree (low-degree) nodes in B network, while the DL refers to the fact that high-degree nodes in A network link low-degree nodes in B network. We investigate the robustness of the interdependent networks constructed by two artificial networks and the power grid, taking into account two stages of the cascading propagation. We numerically find that both the different link patterns and the parameters in the cascading model have important effects on dramatically improving the robustness of the interdependent networks against cascading failures. In addition, we obtain the better link pattern and the matching network structure to effectively avoid the cascading propagation.','This paper explores different ways of assigning link patterns for interdependent links. They use assortative, dissasortative and random link patterns. They adopt the normalized avalanche size S to quantify the robustness. They also define capacities and load properties. They say that the cascading failure occur in 2 stages (one for dependence and the other for load failures). When a node fails the load is redistributed between the neighbours of the failed node proportionaly to their capacities. Cai = (1+beta)k^alfa_ai is the capacitie. They also define p(s) to cuantify robustness, p(s) denotes the proportion between the number of the increased failed nodes in the interdependent networks and the number of the failed nodes in the single BA networks (barabasi-albert),  the smaller the value p(s), the stronger the robustness of the interdependent networks against cascading failures.','journal'),('￼Robustness of network of networks with interdependent and interconnected links','ScienceDirect','Robustness-of-network',2014,'Robustness of network of networks (NON) has been studied only for dependency coupling (Gao et al., 2012) and only for connectivity coupling (Leicht and Souza, arxiv:0907.0894). The case of network of networks with both interdependent and interconnected links is more complicated, and also more close to real-life coupled network systems. Understanding the robustness of NON with interdependent and interconnected links is helpful to design resilient infrastructures. Here we develop a framework to study analytically and numerically the robustness of this system with no-feedback and feedback conditions for the case of starlike NON. When assumed that all degree distributions of the connectivity intra and inter-links are Poissonian, we find that the system undergoes from second order through hybrid order to first order phase transition as coupling strength q increases. Additionally, for both conditions, the results suggest that increasing density of connectivity links (intra-connectivity links or inter-connectivity links) can increase the robustness of the system, while the interdependency links decrease its robustness. Furthermore, by comparing critical attacking strength under same parameters for both conditions, we also find that feedback condition of dependency links, in contrast to no-feedback condition, makes the system extremely vulnerable. Although our detailed analysis is for Poisson degree distribution, the theory can be applied to any degree distribution and other basic topological structure of network such like tree-like and loop-like NON.','This network uses a model that can contain more than 2 networks and that posseses 2 kinds of links: connectivity links (that may act as a bridge to unite connected components even on different networks) and dependency links that represent the dependency between nodes (if a node loses its dependency link dies). This model can has different coupling strength, degree distribution, fractions of nodes in one network depending on nodes of other network and it can have or not the feedback condition (no feedback condition = \"one to one\" model). They use percolation threshold to study the robustnes as well as size of the largest connected component. Note here that the largest connected component may include node clusters that within the network appear disconnected but looking at the overall system are connected to the largest connected component through a connectivity link. They define the hybrid percolation transition (there is a discontinuity point but it doesn\'t desintegrate the network to 0). They find that the higher the number of connectivity links the stronger the system (network of networks, NON) but the higher the amount of dependency links the worst the robustners of the NON.','journal');
